snippet.textDisplay: For those who don't understand the repercussions of the movie "Split." The creator of Split actually talked to DID experts and studied others with DID to get into the role. And when they told him that this movie would be bad for our community, perpetuating stigma, and advised against it's making, they asked if he could provide a disclaimer that having DID doesn't make a person dangerous, he stopped all contact with them. The problem is having a horror movie with a person with DID as an antagonist, when DID is under-researched, highly stimatized, to where family and friends cut off contact with the individual after learning of diagnostics, psychology professors skip over 'DID' because they don't think it needs to be covered, therapists refuse to treat and even not believe in the disorder, and treatment services aren't available. When you're putting millions of dollars into something to be seen, globally, it's a huge F-U to the community affected. Especially when there is no other media showing DID systems in a positive light (having beautiful relationships, going to school, succeeding in a career, saving the world, etc). For most, Split is the very first introduction to the disorder. Historically, whether entertaining or not, it was a low-class move, one that the DID community is having to pay for continuously. :(

snippet.textDisplay: This video is really frustrating to me because DID is so rare and it’s not something you can “switch” easily to. The triggers have to be intense, INTENSE intense beyond your imagination, for you to switch. And you don’t have names or different voices or anything when switching. This isn’t something common at all, a lot of people tend to fake this disorder. You don’t just randomly switch over. It comes from from pure, intense, trauma. What I’m getting to, is this is fake. And really, because some of these people are faking it they are Disrespecting the actual community of people who have DID. This is really bad, Anthony. Kinda disappointed in this

snippet.textDisplay: I really like how Anthony made sure that everyone who switched out knew that they could take as much time as they needed and made sure that when they were "fully out" or not still in the switchy state that  they knew what was going on and made sure that they were okay with answering. I especially love how Anthony treated the little. He was very respectful to them. He constantly made sure that they were okay with answering and let them talk.  The way I immediately pictured the situation in my head was sort of like he was interviewing a "parent" or another person and a child ran in the room and wanted to answer questions too and the other person got up to go to the bathroom or something. He took it as "okay I'm talking to a child so I need to make sure that they understand what is going on and that they don't have to do this if they don't want to." When the little got teary eyed Anthony immediately made sure that they knew that they could take all the time that they needed and if afterwards they didn't want it in the video then it wouldn't be in the video. He was over all very respectful to everyone in the video not just dissociaDID.
